::section{#introduction}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Motivation for sparse attention in long-context LLMs and limitations of existing dense mechanisms."
::

# Introduction

Since the introduction of the Transformer architecture @cite{vaswani2017}, 
self-attention has become the de facto standard for sequence modeling. 
However, the $O(n^2)$ complexity of the attention matrix calculation makes 
it prohibitively expensive for contexts exceeding 8k tokens. 

Sparse attention @cite{child2019} offers a potential solution by only 
computing a subset of the attention scores. We introduce a tiled sparse kernel 
that optimizes memory layout for modern GPU architectures.

::endsection


::section{#methods}
::meta
type: methods
summary: "Description of the tiled sparse attention kernel and the block-level sparsity pattern."
::

# Methodology

Our approach relies on a block-sparse pattern where the attention matrix 
is divided into $64 \times 64$ blocks. Only blocks within a specific 
Hamming distance of the diagonal are computed.

::equation{#eq-attention}
$$
\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\left(\frac{Q K^T \odot M}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right) V
$$
::label Sparse Attention masked according to the block matrix M
::endequation

The mask matrix $M$ is defined at the block level, allowing for coalesced memory access.

::endsection


::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Comparative performance metrics between dense and sparse attention kernels."
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Results

Testing was conducted on NVIDIA H100 GPUs using context lengths ranging from 4k to 64k.

::chart{#tbl-performance}
::title Latency (ms) comparison across sequence lengths
::interpretation
As shown in the table, our sparse kernel begins to outperform the standard 
FlashAttention-2 implementation at sequence lengths $\geq 16k$. At $64k$, the 
latency is reduced by over $2.5\times$ compared to the dense baseline.
::
| Sequence Length | Dense Latency (ms) | Sparse Latency (ms) | Speedup |
|-----------------|--------------------|---------------------|---------|
| 4,096           | 12.4               | 14.1                | 0.88x   |
| 8,192           | 45.2               | 42.1                | 1.07x   |
| 16,384          | 192.5              | 115.3               | 1.67x   |
| 32,768          | 840.4              | 410.2               | 2.05x   |
| 65,536          | 3520.1             | 1380.5              | 2.55x   |
::endchart

::endsection


::section{#conclusion}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "Final summary of the sparse kernel's impact on long-context processing."
depends_on: ["#results"]
::

# Conclusion

We have demonstrated that block-level sparsity combined with custom tiled 
kernels can significantly alleviate the attention bottleneck. Future work 
will explore dynamic sparsity patterns that adapt to input content.

::endsection
